<p>We offer a visual hull inspection service, and we're always careful about what we call it. It's a visual condition report — not a marine survey, not a structural assessment, and not a replacement for a qualified surveyor's opinion. But within those boundaries, it's a remarkably useful tool that fills a gap most boat owners don't even know exists: affordable, repeatable, documented hull intelligence between your annual haul-outs.</p>

<h2>What Our Inspection Shows You</h2>

<p>Our Keelcrab Pro's onboard HD camera provides a comprehensive visual record of your hull below the waterline. Here's what we're looking at during a typical inspection:</p>

<p><strong>Antifouling condition.</strong> This is often the most valuable element for owners. We can see where your antifouling is thick and healthy, where it's thinning, where primer is showing through, and where the coating has failed entirely. This information helps you decide whether to repaint before the next season or whether your existing coating has another year of life in it — potentially saving you £800-1,500 in unnecessary repaint costs.</p>

<p><strong>Fouling coverage and type.</strong> We document the type of fouling present (biofilm, algae, barnacles, tubeworms), its distribution across the hull, and its severity. This baseline information is particularly useful if you're tracking how quickly your hull fouls between cleans — it helps us recommend the optimal cleaning frequency for your specific boat and berth.</p>

<p><strong>Through-hull fittings and intakes.</strong> Blocked or partially obstructed water intakes are a common finding, particularly in Brixham's nutrient-rich harbour. We check each visible through-hull for obstruction, fouling, and general condition. A blocked engine cooling intake on a busy summer day can leave you stranded — better to spot it during a planned inspection than discover it at full throttle.</p>

<p><strong>Keel and rudder condition.</strong> We inspect the visible surfaces of the keel, keel bolts (where visible), rudder blade, and rudder bearing. We're looking for obvious physical damage, unusual corrosion, fouling accumulation in recesses, and anything that looks different from what we'd expect on a well-maintained vessel of that type.</p>

<p><strong>General hull surface.</strong> Dents, scratches, osmotic blistering, crazing, and any anomalies in the hull surface are documented. While we can't determine the structural significance of these findings (that's a surveyor's job), we can tell you they're there and give you a visual record that you can share with a professional for further assessment.</p>

<h2>What Our Inspection Doesn't Tell You</h2>

<p>Being transparent about limitations is as important as describing capabilities. Our inspection cannot determine:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Structural integrity.</strong> We can see surface conditions, but we cannot assess the structural strength of your hull, deck, or keel attachment. If you need structural assurance, you need a surveyor with appropriate testing equipment.</li>
  <li><strong>Osmosis depth and severity.</strong> We can identify surface blistering that may indicate osmotic absorption, but we cannot measure moisture content or determine whether osmosis has progressed to a point requiring remediation. A moisture meter survey is the appropriate tool for this.</li>
  <li><strong>Internal conditions.</strong> Our camera sees the outside of your hull. Engine mountings, internal laminate condition, bulkhead bonding, and other internal factors are entirely outside our scope.</li>
  <li><strong>Compliance status.</strong> We cannot certify your vessel for MCA coding, insurance compliance, or classification society standards. These require accredited surveyors with specific qualifications.</li>
</ul>

<h2>When to Choose Inspection vs Survey</h2>

<p>Our visual inspection is the right choice when you want to check your antifouling condition between haul-outs, monitor fouling progression, document your hull's condition at a specific date, get a quick visual assessment before or after a voyage, or keep a running record of hull condition over time.</p>

<p>A qualified marine survey is the right choice when you're buying or selling a boat, making an insurance claim, preparing for MCA coding or recoding, investigating suspected structural damage, or need a professional opinion on osmosis or delamination.</p>

<p>The two services complement each other rather than compete. Several of our clients use our inspections for routine monitoring and commission a full survey every 3-5 years or when a specific concern arises. The inspection keeps them informed between surveys; the survey provides the professional assessment when it's needed.</p>

<h2>The Documentation Value</h2>

<p>One underappreciated aspect of our inspection is the documentation it creates. Every inspection produces timestamped HD video footage and a written report. This creates a chronological record of your hull's condition that's useful for multiple purposes: demonstrating maintenance diligence to insurers, tracking antifouling performance over multiple seasons, providing evidence of hull condition at the time of a sale or purchase, and giving your yard manager precise information about what needs attention during the next haul-out.</p>

<p>At £10 per metre with a £100 minimum charge, a visual inspection is one of the most cost-effective pieces of hull intelligence available to a boat owner. It won't replace a surveyor, but it fills the gaps between surveys with practical, visual, documented information that helps you make better maintenance decisions.</p>

